emistry Steps";s:3:"alt";s:15:"chemistry steps";s:3:"url";s:106:"https://www.chemistrysteps.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/D-galactose-OH-groups-pointing-up-and-down-1.png";s:5:"thumb";s:123:"https://encrypted-tbn0.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcQqYzY3ozokQBvxOmGHpWZoKhZvyyom6_DLLv9gkXPS5XMTA8_vF2ilY2N5OnfmIhcrlpA";s:8:"filetype";s:3:"png";s:5:"width";i:450;s:6:"height";i:1243;s:6:"source";s:78:"https://www.chemistrysteps.com/converting-fischer-haworth-chair-carbohydrates/";s:6:"domain";s:22:"www.chemistrysteps.com";}i:18;a:11:{s:7:"keyword";s:25:"ketose chair conformation";s:4:"slug";s:25:"ketose-chair-conformation";s:5:"title";s:74:"Carbohydrates Haworth Fischer Projections With Chair Conformations Youtube";s:3:"alt";s:7:"youtube";s:3:"url";s:48:"https://i.ytimg.com/vi/7FR2_VjwKYk/mqdefault.jpg";s:5:"thumb";s:123:"https://encrypted-tbn0.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcRFSzkJOqugE2dwOPoPrKE13U8bNRnYnANZAWS4RMU9ZaUbHyFIsq8nW_t_2vXKlgfB7ZI";s:8:"filetype";s:3:"jpg";s:5:"width";i:180;s:6:"height";i:320;s:6:"source";s:43:"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7FR2_VjwKYk";s:6:"domain";s:15:"www.youtube.com";}i:19;a:11:{s:7:"keyword";s:25:"ketose chair conformation";s:4:"slug";s:25:"ketose-chair-conformation";s:5:"title";s:75:"Converting Fischer Haworth And Chair Forms Of Carbohydrates Chemistry Steps";s:3:"alt";s:15:"chemistry steps";s:3:"url";s:129:"https://www.chemistrysteps.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/Converting-a-Carbohydrate-Fischer-Projection-To-A-Haworth-and-Chair.png";s:5:"thumb";s:123:"https://encrypted-tbn0.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcQzlW5QT2mbVgZxaGn9xdNhZFcr5DLuhcUT8hsG0MxbDlFcFIAMIZ4qYyThYSS1TrUMnuU";s:8:"filetype";s:3:"png";s:5:"width";i:2193;s:6:"height";i:1133;s:6:"source";s:78:"https://www.chemistrysteps.com/converting-fischer-haworth-chair-carbohydrates/";s:6:"domain";s:22:"www.chemistrysteps.com";}i:20;a:11:{s:7:"keyword";s:25:"ketose chair conformation";s:4:"slug";s:25:"ketose-chair-conformation";s:5:"title";s:61:"Peptide Synthesis Custom Peptide Fmoc Amino Acids Chempep Inc";s:3:"alt";s:7:"chempep";s:3:"url";s:62:"https://www.chempep.com/ChemPep-Generic-Term_clip_image030.jpg";s:5:"thumb";s:90:"https://encrypted-tbn0.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcSaLI__GErHR7Z4kecMrbmdTuTtqKzyBeTImQ";s:8:"filetype";s:3:"jpg";s:5:"width";i:255;s:6:"height";i:378;s:6:"source";s:55:"https://www.chempep.com/ChemPep-Generic-Term_Others.htm";s:6:"domain";s:15:"www.chempep.com";}}s:9:"sentences";a:55:{i:0;s:260:"Bch 4053 Biochemistry I Aldose Vs Ketose Chair Conformation Chair Conformation Ochempal Aldoses vs Ketoses An aldose is a monosaccharide that has an aldehyde group at the end and a ketose is one which has a keto functional group typically residing on Carbon 2.";i:1;s:79:"Https D3bv2hg4q0qyg2 Cloudfront Net 2017 12 20 Ph161 E01 T02 Carbohydrates Pdf.";i:2;s:135:"Fischer Projections Haworth Structures and Chair Conformers The acyclic structure of a sugar is commonly drawn as a Fischer projection.";i:3;s:132:"These structures make it easy to show the conﬁguration at each stereogenic center in the molecule without using wedges and dashes.";i:4;s:68:"Fischer projections also allow an easy classiﬁcation of the sugar.";i:5;s:26:"Draw the Hs and OH groups.";i:6;s:109:"All the groups on the right side in the Fischer projection point down the groups on the left are pointing up.";i:7;s:54:"Convert the Haworth to a chair conformation if needed.";i:8;s:103:"The groups pointing up in a Haworth stay up in the chair and down stay down either axial or equatorial.";i:9;s:40:"Steps for Converting Fischer to Haworth.";i:10;s:108:"Now to make a cyclic hemiacetal from your linear Fischer projection youll need to follow a few simple steps.";i:11;s:47:"Draw a Haworths stem like in the picture above.";i:12;s:84:"Number your atoms 1 through 5 starting from the anomeric carbon and going clockwise.";i:13;s:180:"To determine the chair conformation of a hexose it is generally easiest to draw it and compare it with -D-glucose where all heavy groups are equatorial and the conformation is 4C1.";i:14;s:196:"If the number of heavy axial groups becomes smaller when the conformation is changed to 1C4 all equatorial groups in 4C1 become axial and vice versa then it is likely that the conformation is 1C4.";i:15;s:37:"D-Fructose is the most common ketose.";i:16;s:198:"Pyranose sugars assume a chair conformation based in part on maximizing the number of large groups OH and CH 2 OH at equatorial positions which are less sterically hindered than are axial positions.";i:17;s:70:"The 4 C 1 conformation in which C4 is above and C1 is below the plane.";i:18;s:131:"Ketose rearrances to mixture of aldoses which can be oxidized by Cu 2 reagents either as the open chain form or as the cyclic form.";i:19;s:157:"Glucose the building unit of starch and cellulose is a six-membered ring that adopts a chair conformation and as a result it has axial and equatorial groups.";i:20;s:187:"The only difference when making the polymer is that the oxygen in starch linking the units uses one equatorial and one axial bond while in cellulose it links them by two equatorial bonds.";i:21;s:110:"The cyclohexane ring 1 being large is flexible and therefore could assume an infinite number of conformations.";i:22;s:86:"The most stable conformation of the cyclohexane ring is called the chair conformation.";i:23;s:102:"The chair conformation is customarily drawn either as 2 or as 3 which are mirror images of each other.";i:24;s:82:"In the chair comformation the internal bond angle at a carbon atom is 1114º very.";i:25;s:104:"The Boat conformation is less stable than the Chair recognizable by eclipsed bonds at four Carbon atoms.";i:26;s:57:"This entry was tagged aldose hemiacetal hemiketal ketose.";i:27;s:23:"Bookmark the permalink.";i:28;s:128:"Ketose D-Monosaccharide Pyranose Triose L-Monosaccharide Glycoside Tetrose Hemiacetal Glycosidic Bond Pentose Anomeric Carbon 1.";i:29;s:154:"Draw one example of each of the following types of monosaccharides there may be several correct answers and indicate the number of possible stereoisomers.";i:30;s:34:"108B Carbohydrate Activity Author.";i:31;s:138:"In the chair conformation look at the bond angles at the different positions of the sugars that indicate down or up on the ring structure.";i:32;s:170:"The squiggly line at C-1 indicates that ring closure could create either new anomer the alpha in the down or trans conformation or the beta in the up or cis conformation.";i:33;s:96:"Carbohydrates are really just polyhydroxyaldehydes the aldosesor polyhydroxyketones the ketoses.";i:34;s:63:"So for a carbohydrate to be an aldoseit needs an aldehydegroup.";i:35;s:79:"Remember that an aldehyde group here shown as CHO is also often written as CHO.";i:36;s:41:"And to be a ketoseit needs a ketonegroup.";i:37;s:179:"In the ketose shown the ketone group becomes C-2 the carbon atom next to the top Most common sugars are aldoses rather than ketoses so our discussion will focus mainly on aldoses.";i:38;s:61:"The other carbon atoms are numbered in sequence from the top.";i:39;s:75:"The chair conformation and the Haworth projections are alternative ways of.";i:40;s:180:"To determine the chair conformation of a hexose it is generally easiest to draw it and compare it with -D-glucose where all heavy groups are equatorial and the conformation is 4C1.";i:41;s:196:"If the number of heavy axial groups becomes smaller when the conformation is changed to 1C4 all equatorial groups in 4C1 become axial and vice versa then it is likely that the conformation is 1C4.";i:42;s:30:"Fischer to Haworth Projection.";i:43;s:127:"This video gives an elaborate explanation on how the cyclic Haworth projection is formed from the open chain Fischer projectio.";i:44;s:81:"Due to the multiple chiral centers along a linear carbon chain for carbohydrates.";i:45;s:84:"Emil Fischer developed the Fischer Projection in order to represent these compounds.";i:46;s:42:"Remember how to draw a Fischer projection.";i:47;s:55:"1 View 